name: Wow! Signal
notes: A strong narrowband radio signal detected by Jerry R. Ehman while working on a SETI project at Ohio State University. The signal lasted for 72 seconds and has not been explained or detected again.

name: SHGb02+14a
notes: A transient narrowband radio signal detected by SETI@home. It showed Doppler drift consistent with a celestial source but was never observed again.

name: Arecibo Message
notes: A binary-encoded message sent from the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico towards the M13 globular star cluster. It contained information about humanity and Earth.

name: Cosmic Call 1
notes: A METI transmission sent from the Evpatoria RT-70 radio telescope toward four nearby Sun-like stars including 16 Cygni.

name: Teen Age Message
notes: A METI transmission from Evpatoria composed of music and messages created by teenagers, sent toward six nearby stars including HD 197076.

name: Cosmic Call 2
notes: A follow-up METI message sent from Evpatoria toward five stellar systems including Gliese 49.

name: Across the Universe
notes: A continuous transmission of the Beatles song 'Across the Universe' sent from NASA's Madrid Deep Space Network antenna toward Polaris to celebrate the song's 40th anniversary.

name: A Message From Earth
notes: A digital radio signal sent from Evpatoria, targeting Gliese 581, containing 501 messages, images, and songs from a Bebo social media contest, aiming to spark interest in SETI.

name: Hello From Earth
notes: A digital message collection transmitted from Canberra (Tidbinbilla) toward the Gliese 581 system, containing public messages submitted via the internet.

name: Wow! Reply
notes: A crowdsourced interstellar message transmitted from the Arecibo Observatory toward the original Wow! Signal coordinates to commemorate its 35th anniversary.

name: Lone Signal
notes: A crowdfunded Active SETI project that sent short messages from Jamesburg Earth Station in California toward Gliese 526.

name: A Simple Response
notes: 'A Simple Response to an Elemental Message' containing 3775 worldwide responses to the question: 'How will our present, environmental interactions shape the future?' Transmitted from the Cebreros station in Madrid, Spain, toward Polaris.
